---
Midgaard's governance tradition does not claim direct descent from the Keepers of Measure, but the logical structure of its charter system — registry primacy, witnessed transactions, public tribunal — is recognizably derived from Measure Script's dual-function inscription tradition.
The First Stone Accord's founding practice of documenting all transactions at watched squares is a direct practical echo of Keeper survey stations, where all significant exchanges had to be witnessed and inscribed to be legally binding.
Midgaard's Charter Sovereignty office holds Keeper-era survey documents in its deep archive as "pre-charter precedent" — legally non-binding but historically authoritative for questions about which institutions have governed specific territories longest.
The pre-charter precedent archive is the basis for several Midgaard rulings that favored historical Keeper governance over more recent competing claims — Midgaard's institutional self-interest aligns with treating Keeper precedent as legitimate because Midgaard claims institutional continuity with the Keeper tradition.
The Reckoning faction notes the selective application: Keeper precedent is cited when it supports Midgaard's claims and not cited when it would support non-human corridor communities' claims.
The Keepers' formal documentation of non-human corridor peoples in survey records — without granting institutional standing — is the template that Midgaard's intake classification system reproduces: documented, registered, categorized, but not made fully civic.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Jade Magistracy has independently traced its notation system back to the Keepers' Littoral Branch through comparative document analysis.
The reconstruction project was motivated by the discovery that Mafdet's Ledger Houses use a similar notation — the shared origin in Littoral Branch script was confirmed when the Jade Clerks found maritime trade documents that use the same volumetric-legal glyph combinations.
The Jade Magistracy's reconstruction places their institutional lineage in the maritime Keeper tradition rather than the inland tradition Midgaard claims — a significant political assertion, since it means Kowloon's governance system is not derivative of Midgaard's charter tradition but is a parallel descendant of the same pre-charter source.
Research expeditions seeking Littoral Branch source documents at the Saltglass Reach Wardens' cairn tablet library are ongoing; the Reach Wardens' condition (information exchange) and Mafdet's concern about commercial monopoly have complicated the expeditions.
House Qo's descendants — the modern Courier Lantern Office — preserve Littoral Branch notation techniques in their relay station inscription practices, a transmission that survived the Ashfall Monsoon and Kowloon's founding disruption intact.
The Neon Covenant's founding inscription was made in phosphorescent squid dye partly because Littoral Branch tradition required maritime-origin materials for founding documents — a practice preserved from Keeper coastal archive methods.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess's founding archivists documented Keeper-era survey records during foundation excavations at the Evermeet ruins site.
The excavation records show that Evermeet had been a Keeper survey station before it became a fortified city — the watch-square layout of Evermeet's ruins matches Keeper administrative compound geometry.
Kiess's institutional design therefore sits directly on a Keeper administrative site, giving Kiess the most literal physical continuity with Keeper governance of any modern city.
The three-power governance structure (Syndic Council, Warden Circle, Covenant Bench) was partly modeled on the Keeper survey station's three functional divisions: measurement and record, route enforcement, and dispute arbitration.
Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant doctrine addresses a failure that the Keeper system contained in potential: Measure Script's dual-function inscription meant that describing a person's status and legally fixing that status were the same act. The potential for institutional abuse was structural.
The obsidian disc bearing the Spirebound Conclave's seal is held by the Syndic Council alongside Keeper-era survey fragments recovered from the Evermeet excavation — an institutional pairing asserting that Kiess understands both the civilization that preceded its site and the abuses that followed.

