---
Rakuen's Garden Ledger system uses accounting formats that trace to Keeper inland-branch survey notation through Midgaard's standardized ledger conventions.
The accounting conversion Rakuen performed after the Southmark Petition's refusal — adopting Midgaard ledger standards — moved Rakuen's accounting further from the Keeper survey format and closer to Midgaard's charter-derived system.
Rakuen's Compact Purist faction views this conversion as an institutional concession that yielded nothing: Rakuen adopted Midgaard's accounting standards, the next petition refusal cited different grounds.
The Keeper tradition is referenced in Rakuen political discourse primarily through the Reed Law connection: the Water Court's Burn Ledger emergency reallocation framework preserves Keeper survey law's most practically important feature — the principle that described circumstances create legal obligations.
Rakuen's constitutional scholars have proposed that a Keeper-tradition argument for annexation — based on the historical survey maps showing Rakuen's territory as part of the integrated road network — would be more persuasive than the charter-sovereignty argument Midgaard used to refuse the Iron Compact Appeal.
The proposal requires the Keeper survey documents that place Rakuen's territory within the integrated network; those documents are in Midgaard's pre-charter precedent archive.

