---
Mafdet's Ledger Houses are the living institutional descendants of the Keepers' Littoral Branch.
The maritime legal notation Mafdet uses for cargo manifests, oath attestations, and harbor tariff records is a direct descendant of Littoral Branch Measure Script — the volumetric-legal glyph combinations in use in Mafdet today were documented in Keeper coastal survey records.
This institutional lineage gives Mafdet a governance legitimacy claim that is neither derivative of Midgaard's charter tradition nor in competition with it: the Littoral Branch and the inland branch are parallel descendants of the same Keeper system.
Mafdet's concern about Kowloon's Littoral Branch reconstruction project is that successful reconstruction would give Kowloon institutional standing in the maritime legal tradition — potentially creating a competing center of Littoral Branch authority.
The Saltglass Reach Wardens' cairn tablet library contains Littoral Branch source documents that Mafdet's Ledger Houses have already accessed; they have not disclosed what those documents contain, consistent with the Reach Wardens' information-exchange condition.
The Strandline Compact's founding document was inscribed using Littoral Branch notation, making it readable by Keeper-tradition scholars as a founding document with deeper institutional genealogy than Mafdet typically publicizes.

