---
Kethari water-memory predates and exceeds any Keeper survey record of the Saltglass Reach's subsurface water systems.
Keeper survey crews formally documented Kethari as "knowledgeable about subsurface water systems" but failed to recognize that Kethari water-memory of the aquifer exceeded and predated any Keeper measurement.
The Aquifer Covenant governing Deepwell Confluence water-source claims was administered by Kethari communities before the Keepers arrived; Keeper survey law overlaid the Aquifer Covenant without replacing it, creating a dual-system arrangement that the Keepers documented without understanding its significance.
When the Salt Ledger Kingdoms converted Keeper survey law into hereditary authority, the Aquifer Covenant survived intact underneath — because Kethari water-memory transmission is oral and multi-generational, it did not depend on the administrative infrastructure that the kingdoms took over.
The Keepers' survey records of Kethari territorial claims are the earliest human-written documentation of the Aquifer Covenant's existence; Kethari elders view these records as technically accurate but contextually misleading — they describe the covenant's surface features without understanding the water-memory tradition that gives it authority.
Modern Kethari alarm regarding any institution that attempts to reduce water-memory to registry documentation traces to the Keeper period: the Keepers documented Kethari knowledge without incorporating Kethari governance, which created the template for all subsequent institutional engagements with Kethari communities.
Calibrated alarm is the appropriate Kethari response to institutions bearing writing systems: documentation and institutional incorporation have historically been sequential, not simultaneous.

